untry. Adams struggled to create a nation virtuous enough to sustain a republican government, and Madison worked to establish a government based on justice. Giving a new context to the founders' mission, Trees studies their contributions not simply as policy prescriptions but in terms of a more elusive and symbolic level of action. His work illuminates the tangled relationship among rhetoric, politics, self, and nation--as well as the larger question of national identity that remains with us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAlien and Sedition Acts.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAntifederalists.  aBingham, William.  aBrackenridge, Hugh Henry.  aBurroughs, Stephen.  aCabot, George.  aCharlotte Temple.  aConstitutional Convention.  aContinental Congress.  aCruger, Catherine Church.  aDeclaration of Independence.  aEuripides.  aFederalist Papers.  aFederalists.  aFreneau, Philip.  aFries Rebellion.  aGender.  aGentility.  aGerry, Elbridge.  aGranger, Gideon.  aGreat Britain.  aHabermas, Jurgen.  aHippolytus.  aHutcheson, Frances.  aIrving, Washington.  aJefferson, Thomas.  aJohnson, Samuel.  aKing, Rufus.  aKnox, Henry.  aLivingston, Susanna.  aMadison, Dolley.  aMonroe, James.  aMuhlenberg, Frederick.  aNullification.  aPickering, Timothy.  aPolitical culture.  aPublius.  aRepublicanism.  aScottish enlightenment.  aSterne, Laurence.  aTazewell, Henry.  aVenable, Abraham.  aWarner, Michael.  aWarren, James.  aWashington, George.  aWebster, Noah.  aWhiskey Rebellion.  aWills, Garry.  aWolcott, Oliver.  aXYZ Affair.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691233536zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691233536423Cove